[Matthew 4:21](../../../bib/kjv/mat004.htm#021.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_021">mat 4:21</span></span>

James

Two persons are called by this name in the New Testament.

\(1\) James the son of Zebedee, an apostle ([Mat
10:2](../../../bib/kjv/mat010.htm#002).md) and the brother of the apostle
John, apart from whom he is never mentioned, and with whom, together
with Peter, he was admitted to the especial intimacy of our Lord. ([Mat
17:1](../../../bib/kjv/mat017.htm#001).md); ([Mar
5:37](../../../bib/kjv/mar005.htm#037).md); ([Mar
9:2](../../../bib/kjv/mar009.htm#002).md); ([Mar
14:33](../../../bib/kjv/mar014.htm#033).md) He was martyred by Herod. ([Act
12:2](../../../bib/kjv/act012.htm#002).md).

\(2\) A son of Alphaeus (or Cleopas) and Mary the sister of Mary the
mother of Jesus.

(See Scofield) - ([Mat 1:16](../../../bib/kjv/mat001.htm#016).md)

and brother of Joses. ([Mar 15:40](../../../bib/kjv/mar015.htm#040).md). He
was, therefore, a cousin of the Lord Jesus. He is called James "the
less" ([Mar 15:40](../../../bib/kjv/mar015.htm#040).md) Literally, little,
that is, Of shorter stature than James the son of Zebedee). He was an
apostle. ([Mat 10:3](../../../bib/kjv/mat010.htm#003).md) It has been
conjectured that "Lebbaeus, whose surname was Thaddaeus" ([Mat
10:3](../../../bib/kjv/mat010.htm#003).md) was identical with the Juda of
([Luk 6:16](../../../bib/kjv/luk006.htm#016).md) who is there called
"ofthat is, 'son' or 'brother' as is has been variously translated\]
James." A Juda is mentioned with a James and Joses and Simon in ([Mar
6:3](../../../bib/kjv/mar006.htm#003).md) as "brother" of our Lord

(See Scofield) - ([Mat 13:55](../../../bib/kjv/mat013.htm#055).md), margin
reference). ([Mat 13:55](../../../bib/kjv/mat013.htm#055).md).

The Gospels mention no other James who could be called the brother of
the Lord Jesus, but James the less was certainly the son of Alphaeus and
Mary the sister of our Lord's mother. The conclusion seems, therefore
most probable that; ([Mat 10:3](../../../bib/kjv/mat010.htm#003).md); ([Mat
13:55](../../../bib/kjv/mat013.htm#055).md); ([Mar
3:18](../../../bib/kjv/mar003.htm#018).md); ([Mar
6:3](../../../bib/kjv/mar006.htm#003).md); ([Luk
6:15](../../../bib/kjv/luk006.htm#015).md); ([Act
1:13](../../../bib/kjv/act001.htm#013).md); ([Act
12:17](../../../bib/kjv/act012.htm#017).md); ([Mar
15:13](../../../bib/kjv/mar015.htm#013).md); ([Mar
21:18](../../../bib/kjv/mar021.htm#018).md); ([Gal
1:19](../../../bib/kjv/gal001.htm#019).md); ([Gal
2:9](../../../bib/kjv/gal002.htm#009).md); ([Gal
2:12](../../../bib/kjv/gal002.htm#012).md); ([Jam
1:1](../../../bib/kjv/jam001.htm#001).md) refer to James the less, son of
Alphaeus and Mary, and cousin, or, according to Jewish usage, "brother"
of the Lord Jesus. He was the author of the Epistle of James.

